counts the most disastrous flood in the history of California and the West, which occurred in 1861-62. The authors show that, while the West may have temporarily buffered itself from such harsh climatic swings by creating artificial environments and human landscapes, our modern civilization may be ill-prepared for the future climate changes that are predicted to beset the region. They warn that it is time to face the realities of the past and prepare for a future in which fresh water may be less reliable.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aClimatic changesxEnvironmental aspectsxWest (U.S.). 0aClimatic changesxForecastingxWest (U.S.). 0aClimatic changeszWest (U.S.) 0aClimatic changeszWest (U.S.)xForecasting. 0aHydrologyxWest (U.S.)xUnited States, West. 0aHydrologyzWest (U.S.) 7aNATURE / Ecology.2bisacsh1 aMalamud-Roam, Frances, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520954809423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520954809.jpg  a978-3-11-066334-1  UC Press eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-069042-2  UC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles